    <section id="artie" class="content-section content-urgent">
      <div class="urgent-box">
        <h2>This section is for Artie</h2>
        <p>Artie had FIV, hyperthyroidism, and asthma — and then developed neurological symptoms and a dropping body temperature. FIP negative. No cancer found on cytology. We had planned radioactive iodine treatment for his thyroid. Instead, we made the sad choice to put him down at the vet as his decline accelerated without an explanation.</p>
        <p>The answer never came. That experience — the gap, the unanswered question, the feeling of failing your cat because you couldn't find what was wrong — is one of the loneliest places to be. This section is for every owner who is there right now.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="what-neuro" class="content-section">
      <h2>Neurological Signs in Cats</h2>
      <p>Neurological disease in cats can be subtle at first — and is often attributed to other things (old age, arthritis, medication side effects) before it's recognised as neurological. Signs that warrant neurological investigation:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Circling, tilting the head persistently to one side</li>
        <li>Loss of coordination (ataxia) — stumbling, falling, difficulty jumping</li>
        <li>Seizures of any type</li>
        <li>Sudden changes in behaviour or personality</li>
        <li>Weakness in one or more limbs — dragging a leg, knuckling over</li>
        <li>Abnormal eye movements (nystagmus)</li>
        <li>Dropping body temperature below 37.5°C / 99.5°F — a concerning sign</li>
        <li>Changes in pupil size, particularly asymmetric pupils</li>
        <li>Sudden appetite loss or inability to eat that doesn't respond to anti-nausea medication</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>Hypothermia (low body temperature) in a cat is always a serious sign</strong> requiring immediate veterinary attention. It often indicates a systemic problem — not simply a cold environment.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="differential" class="content-section">
      <h2>Differential Diagnoses — What Could It Be?</h2>
      <p>Neurological signs in cats have a long list of possible causes. Working through them systematically is the only way to narrow toward an answer — or to document that the common causes have been ruled out. Major categories:</p>
      <div class="meds-list">
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">FIP (Feline Infectious Peritonitis)</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Can cause neurological signs through inflammation of the nervous system. The standard antibody test (coronavirus titre) is unreliable for diagnosing FIP specifically. PCR testing of CSF (cerebrospinal fluid) or affected tissue gives more definitive results. Artie tested FIP negative — but the test used and the sample type matter significantly. A new antiviral treatment (GS-441524 / GC376) has dramatically changed FIP from a death sentence to a treatable disease in many cases. Ask specifically about this if FIP is on the differential.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Brain tumour</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Primary brain tumours (meningioma is most common in cats) and metastatic cancer can both cause neurological signs. MRI is the diagnostic standard — CT can suggest but not definitively diagnose. Cytology of other tissues does not rule out brain tumour.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Thiamine deficiency</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Neurological signs in cats who have been eating poorly or exclusively eating certain fish-based foods. Thiamine deficiency can cause dramatic neurological deterioration but is highly treatable if caught. Mention this specifically to your vet if your cat has had poor food intake.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Toxin ingestion</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Many common household substances, plants, and medications are toxic to cats and can cause neurological signs. Consider whether anything new has entered the environment.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Hypertensive encephalopathy</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Extremely high blood pressure can cause neurological signs through cerebrovascular damage. Always check blood pressure in a cat with unexplained neurological symptoms — this is treatable.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="med-item">
          <div class="med-name">Vestibular disease</div>
          <div class="med-desc">Idiopathic vestibular syndrome causes sudden severe loss of balance, head tilt, and nystagmus — it can look alarming but often resolves partially or fully without treatment. It is sometimes called "old dog vestibular" but cats get it too. However, it should be a diagnosis of exclusion — not the first assumption.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="diagnostics" class="content-section">
      <h2>Pushing for Answers — The Diagnostic Conversation</h2>
      <p>When basic bloodwork and a physical examination don't explain the neurological signs, more advanced diagnostics are the next step. These require referral to a specialist in most cases:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>MRI or CT of the brain and spine</strong> — requires anaesthesia, which carries risk in a declining cat. Discuss the risk-benefit calculation with a specialist.</li>
        <li><strong>Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) analysis</strong> — can identify inflammation, infection, or cancer cells in the nervous system.</li>
        <li><strong>Specialist referral</strong> — a veterinary neurologist can take the history and examination findings and suggest a targeted diagnostic path. Ask your vet for a referral.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>On the decision to pursue advanced diagnostics:</strong> There is no right answer here. MRI under anaesthesia in a cat who is already declining carries real risk. A diagnosis that comes back as "untreatable" may or may not help you make decisions. These are deeply personal calculations, and there is no version of "should have" or "shouldn't have." We made the choice with Artie to stop pursuing answers when his decline accelerated — that was the right choice for him.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="when-unknown" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living With — and Making Decisions Without — an Answer</h2>
      <p>Sometimes the answer doesn't come. The tests come back negative or inconclusive. The specialists say "we're not sure." Your cat continues to decline and you have to make decisions without knowing why.</p>
      <p>This is one of the hardest situations in pet ownership — the uncertainty compounds the grief. Some things that helped us:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Reframe the goal.</strong> If you can't find the cause, you can still manage the symptoms and maintain quality of life. Pain management, appetite support, and comfort care don't require a diagnosis.</li>
        <li><strong>Document everything.</strong> Keep a brief daily log of appetite, activity, and any new symptoms. This helps you spot trends and provides useful information for the vet.</li>
        <li><strong>Set a quality of life threshold in advance.</strong> When things are still uncertain, decide together: "If X stops happening, or Y starts happening, we will make the hardest call." Having the conversation before you're in crisis makes it slightly less impossible.</li>
        <li><strong>The decision to let go without an answer is not failure.</strong> We did this with Artie. It was one of the hardest things we have done. It was also the right thing.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-questions" class="content-section">
      <h2>Questions to Ask Your Vet</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>What is the differential diagnosis list for these specific symptoms?</li>
        <li>What tests would rule out the most serious or most treatable causes?</li>
        <li>Has blood pressure been measured? Could hypertensive encephalopathy explain this?</li>
        <li>Has thiamine deficiency been considered given the appetite history?</li>
        <li>Should we see a veterinary neurologist? Can you refer us?</li>
        <li>Is FIP still on the table, and if so — has GS-441524 (the new antiviral) been discussed?</li>
        <li>If we can't get a diagnosis, what can we do to keep my cat comfortable?</li>
        <li>How will I know when quality of life has declined to the point where we should consider euthanasia?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

